――Without being told by anyone. Arakiya swallowed it down.

Arakiya: [――――]

With great throbbing, the sound of flowing blood, was enveloped with pain.

That heartbeat pounded faster than it had during the midst of battle, with each thump of the heart becoming a shock akin to a nail being driven directly into the soul, which surged throughout her entire body. Yet, it eased Arakiya's mind.

Knowing that the heart still pumped blood, signified that she still retained her human form.

Even if it had been just a minor comfort akin to margin of error, it was necessary for Arakiya to keep herself from becoming stirred, to keep her soul from scattering.

――The unique existence known as The Spirit Eater in this world, composed solely of Arakiya.

Born from the delusions of individuals who could not be called researchers, but rather aberrants; the taboo existence of the Spirit Eater―― named Arakiya, had been kept alive as a sole being under a destiny shared with no one else in this world.

In a daringly diluted ego, Arakiya, who had clung only to the existence of the "pillar" that she deemed important to herself, had devoured spirits, acted as a formidable being, and fulfilled her role.

She had thought that was enough.

However, it was not as she had realized, upon losing said "pillar”.

Even if she had realized it, it was too late. If The Spirit Eater had ended as it should have, she would have resulted in an early collapse of the ego, consumed by the spirits she had absorbed, and her soul would have been painted over.

However, Arakiya did not meet that fate. Two factors could be considered.

One was that the individual Arakiya had deemed as her "pillar" was like a dazzling sun, shining so brightly that even when they were separated, they couldn't lose sight of them.

The other reason, and one that Arakia would never have admitted―― the days after being separated from the "pillar“, was the constant thunderous reminder of Arakiya's own existence, which shook her soul incessantly, evoking feelings of inferiority and stimulating her individuality.

Bathed in the light of the dazzling sun, accompanied by the incessant thunder, Arakia had preserved her own soul.

???: [――And, that is the conclusion I've come to, but I would like to hear if you have any awareness of it.]

Arakiya: [...No.]

It was the year when Arakyia surpassed Olbart in rank and was promoted to Second.

Chisha's opinion, based on his search relating to the remaining literature on the Spirit Eater, had etched a stern expression on Arakiya's face; the first time ever in their long acquaintance.

It was understandable. Chisha was intelligent, and his explanations were clear, but his perspective had been difficult for Arakiya to accept.

Arakiya herself only understood her existence as a Spirit Eater on a sensory level, yet she wanted to believe that her entirety was made entirely of Prisca.

She did not want that hopeful wish to be diluted by less desirable components.

To begin with――,

Arakiya: [...Why did you bring that up?]

As she questioned, it was surprising in itself that Chisha had broached such a topic.

Arakiya’s “pillar”, Prisca―― her exceptional escape from the Imperial Selection Ceremony, and being allowed to leave the country alive, was the most closely guarded secret within the Vollachian Empire.

At the time, it was natural for Arakiya and Chisha, who were involved in her exile, to know, but it had been a topic they had not spoken of for years, and something not to be mentioned to anyone else.

So why, at this moment, had Chisha chosen to bring it up?

Chisha: [I want to know whether you are a fragile, ephemeral, and vanishing existence or not. Whether I should count you among the numbers for the impending great battle that is yet to come.]

Arakiya: [...It makes no sense. I’m one of the Nine Divine Generals.]

It was only natural that they would have been sent to put down what Chisha and Vincent had predicted was a rebellion.

However, at Arakiya's response, Chisha's eye twitched downwards, forming an unusual expression on his face. It was a smile seldom seen from Chisha, who had almost always wore an expression of either blankness or bewilderment.

With that smile, probing Arakiya's vulnerability, Chisha continued.

Chisha: [The impending battle seems to be a little bigger than what you anticipate. I know that you do not truly serve His Excellency from the depths of your heart, nor do you consider us allies.]

Arakiya: [――――]

Chisha: [Even though I understand, it still stings a bit not to be denied.]

Arakiya: [...For the sake of the princess, I will not disappear.]

Without acknowledging Chisha's reaction as he touched his forehead, Arakiya ran her own hand over her eyepatch.

There was a reason why she was herself, a soul named Arakiya. The concerns Chisha had would not come to pass. It wasn't to reassure Chisha, she declared.

Arakiya: [Also, that has nothing to do with Cecilus.]

Chisha: [Fu. That's just my conjeeecture. If you really want me to admit that you are different, I would like to see Cecilus lose for once.]

Cecilus: [Huuuuuh? Weren't you talking about me just now? What's with Anya and Chisha treating me like I'm an outsider? That is not nice. Could it be about that one? About the slim chances of winning for Anya, who keeps extending her losing streak without learning her lesson?]

Arakiya: [Cecilus, die.]

Eventually, shortly after, a clash with Cecilus began, and Chisha, who wanted to avoid being involved, fled, so there was no opportunity to hear more about it.

Thereafter, there was no recollection of continuing the conversation with Chisha.

???: [――――]

Just a vague thought crossed her mind.

When would the looming great battle that Chisha was concerned about come? And when it did, would she be counted among the numbers?

If the opportunity arose, she would like to hear it.

Arakiya also had a long relationship with Chisha.

Due to their relationship stemming from the Imperial Selection Ceremony where she was separated from Prisca, Arakiya harbored unforgiveness towards Chisha, who was deeply involved in the reasons behind Prisca’s separation.

However, Chisha had taught Arakiya how to read and write. She owed him a debt. For that favor, she was willing to give Chisha the fight he wanted.

――Or perhaps, would this also be attributed to reasons other than Prisca?

She hated Cecilus. Vincent was complicated, but she leaned towards not forgiving him due to what happened to Prisca. Olbart was amusing with his jokes. Goz had an interesting face. Groovy had a sharp tongue but caring, while Moguro would listen without making unpleasant faces. She was not fond of Yorna, but couldn't bring herself to dislike her. Balleroy would occasionally take her for a ride on his flying dragon, and she felt like Madelyn and her tried to avoid seeing each other. She was grateful to Todd.

――Would all of these also be attributed to reasons other than Prisca?

???: [――――]

Feeling as though she might fall apart, torn to shreds, as if losing herself from the very edge of her memories, Arakiya gathered up fragments of "Arakiya“.

If she didn’t do that, her existence would disappear―― that wasn’t the case. 

Arakiya: [...ncess]

Without doing so, she wouldn't be able to restrain the tumultuous turmoil raging threatening to burst out within her.

It was tremendously colossal. Unbelievably heavy. Intolerably twisted. If left unchecked, it would destroy the Empire.

If she couldn’t keep it under control, her “pillar”――Prisca, wouldn’t be protected

That was why Arakiya, without being told by anyone, swallowed it down. Taking the Stone, Muspel, into her own incomparably thin and small body. 

She mustn't let the Empire be destroyed, manipulated by the monster who called herself a Witch, using this Great Spirit.

For that purpose――,

??? : [It seems you have ingested something unpleasant.――Truly, you are troublesome.]

The incessant thunder felt like a hallucination, piecing together a torn-apart soul.

Amidst the torment of the storm of pain and loss, Arakiya continued to gather up, patching together  "Arakiya”, resisting the dispersion of her turbulent existence.

Continuing to resist, enduring. ―― Clinging to the only possibility that stuck in a soul on the brink of destruction.

